uthor argues that these two formations of voice are mutually constitutive and aligned with modern ideologies of democracy and neoliberal economic projects.  This ethnography is set during an extraordinary period in Nepal’s history that has seen a relatively peaceful 1990 revolution that re-established democracy, a Maoist civil war, and the massacre of the royal family.  These dramatic changes have been accompanied by the proliferation of intimate and political discourse in the expanding public sphere, making the figure of voice ever more critical to an understanding of emerging subjectivity, structural change and cultural mediation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCommunicationxPolitical aspectszNepalzKathmandu. 0aMass mediazNepalzKathmandu. 70(DE-601)1047747110(DE-588)4038463-9aMeinungsfreiheit2gnd 70(DE-601)1062350790(DE-588)4037877-9aMassenmedien2gnd 70(DE-601)2348578030(DE-588)4470590-6aMeinungsäußerung2gnd 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  a1990 revolution.  aasia scholars.  aasian studies.  acivic empowerment.  acollective agency.  acultural mediation.  ademocracy.  aeconomic change.  aemotional experiences.  aethnographers.  aethnography.  ahistorians.  ainteractive technologies.  ainteriority.  aintimate voice.  akathmandu.  amaoist civil war.  amedia studies.  amediation.  amodern history.  amodern ideologies.  aneoliberalism.  anepal.  apersonal life.  apolitical history.  apolitical turmoil.  apolitical voice.  apublic intimacy.  apublic speech.  asouth asia.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprin